'''George Alexander Louis Lebour''', MA, DSc, FGS (1847 – 21 February 1918) was an English geologist.<ref name=NatureObit>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=21 February 1918 |title=Obituary: Prof. G. A. Lebour |journal=Nature |volume=100 |issue=2521 |page= |publisher= |doi= |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015038751916;view=1up;seq=585}}</ref>

Lebour was educated at the [[Royal School of Mines]] and was then a staff member of the [[British Geological Survey|Geological Survey]] from 1873 to 1876. At the [[Durham University|Durham College of Science]], he was a lecturer in geological surveying from 1876 to 1879 and then succeeded [[David Page (geologist)|David Page]] as professor of geology upon the latter's death in 1879. Lebour held this professorial chair until his own death in 1918.<ref name=NatureObit/>

He wrote ''Handbook to the Geology and Natural History of Northumberland and Durham'', which went through three editions from 1879 to 1889. He wrote more than 100 papers on carboniferous geology, thermal conductivity of rocks, and underground temperature. He was awarded the [[Murchison Medal]] in 1904.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Lebour, George Alexander Louis|journal=Who's Who|year=1918|page= 1405|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3452406;view=1up;seq=1445}}</ref>

Upon his death, Lebour was survived by his widow Emily and two daughters;<ref>{{cite journal|title=Obituary. Professor George Alexander Louis Lebour|journal=Geological Magazine|date=June 1918|volume=55|issue=6|pages=287–288|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101075890028;view=1up;seq=323}}</ref> another daughter predeceased him. His youngest daughter was the noted marine biologist [[Marie Lebour]].

