{{Infobox information appliance | name = Nima | logo = | image = | caption = | aka = | developer = [[Nima (fka 6SensorLabs)]] | manufacturer = | family = | type = | generation = | lifespan = | discontinued = | media = | os = | power = 320-mAh LiPo battery | soc = | cpu = | memory = | storage = | memory card = | display = [[OLED]] | graphics = | sound = | input = | controllers = | camera = | touchpad = | connectivity = [[Bluetooth low energy]] | platform = | dimensions = Length: 3.5 in Width: 1.0 in Height: 3.1 in | weight = | compatibility= | predecessor = | successor = | related = | website = {{URL|nimasensor.com}} | title = | releasedate = | price = | unitssold = | unitsshipped = | service = | topgame = }}
'''Nima''' is a portable connected food sensor. The first product, a [[gluten]] sensor was released in Fall 2016. The second product, a [[peanut]] sensor is scheduled to be released in the second half of 2018.
== Operation == A food sample is placed in a one-time use capsule, which is inserted into the Nima sensor. Once the test begins, the food is mixed with proprietary antibodies and analyzed by the sensor for approximately two to three minutes. If the sample contains less than twenty parts per million of gluten (the same limit required by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] for gluten-free labeling), or less than ten parts per million of peanut, Nima displays a smiley face; otherwise a "gluten found" or "peanut found" icon is displayed. The device has not been approved by the FDA, although the developers contest that such approval is not necessary because they "are not using it to diagnose or manage disease."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marcus|first1=Mary Brophy|title=Portable gluten test promises to ease dining woes|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/6sensorlabs-portable-gluten-test-promises-to-ease-dining-woes/|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=11 February 2016|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref>
Nima has also developed a companion application for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]], connected through [[Bluetooth]], that allows users to connect with other Nima owners and find allergen information for specific restaurants and packaged foods.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Matchar|first1=Emily|title=Test Your Restaurant Meal for Allergens in Two Minutes|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/innovation/test-your-restaurant-meal-allergens-two-minutes-180956529/|publisher=Smithsonian.com|accessdate=11 February 2016|date=September 9, 2015}}</ref> The company plans to eventually expand its technology to detect other allergens, such as dairy and tree nuts. They are also exploring detection methods for additives, [[Genetically modified organism|GMO]]s, preservatives and possible causes of food poisoning.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zipkin|first1=Nina|title=Avoiding Gluten? Take This New Device Out to Dinner.|url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/251392|publisher=Entrepreneur|accessdate=11 February 2016|date=October 6, 2015}}</ref>
== Reception == Nima was listed among [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]]'s best inventions of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=TIME Staff|title=The 25 Best Inventions of 2015|url=http://time.com/4115398/best-inventions-2015/item/the-sensor-that-sniffs-out-gluten/|publisher=Time|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>
It has also received positive reviews in [[''Popular Science'']] <ref>{{cite web|last1=Chodosh|title=Testing Food for Gluten at Home: The Nima Sensor Review|url=https://www.popsci.com/nima-allergen-sensor-peanuts-gluten|publisher=Popular Science|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> and [[''The Medical Futurist'']] <ref>{{cite web|last1=The Medical Futurist|title=Testing Food for Gluten at Home: The Nima Sensor Review|url=https://medicalfuturist.com/testing-food-gluten-home-nima-sensor-review|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>
